Understanding Java Arrays
Key Characteristics
●	Fixed Length: Once you create an array, you cannot change its size. If you need more room, you have to create a new, larger array.
●	Zero-Indexed: The first element is at index 0, and the last is at length - 1.
●	Type Safety: An int[] can only hold integers; it won't let a String sneak in.
Declaration and Initialization
You can declare an array in two ways:
1.	Declaration with size: int[] numbers = new int[5]; (Initializes with default values, like 0).
2.	Literal initialization: int[] numbers = {10, 20, 30, 40};.
________________________________________
2. Common Manipulations
To work with arrays effectively, you'll perform these core operations:
●	Accessing/Modifying: Using the index (e.g., arr[2] = 50;).
●	Traversing: Using a for loop or an enhanced for-each loop to visit every element.
●	Sorting: Arranging elements in ascending order.
●	Searching: Finding the index of a specific value (Linear or Binary search).
●	Copying: Creating a duplicate or a subset of an array.
________________________________________
3. The java.util.Arrays Utility Class
Java provides a powerhouse class called Arrays that handles the heavy lifting for you. Without it, you'd be writing manual loops for everything.
Method	Description
Arrays.sort(arr)	Sorts the array in ascending order.
Arrays.binarySearch(arr, key)	Finds the index of a value (requires a sorted array).
Arrays.copyOf(arr, newLength)	Clones the array with a new size.
Arrays.equals(arr1, arr2)	Checks if two arrays have the same elements in the same order.
Arrays.toString(arr)	Converts the array to a readable string format.
Arrays.fill(arr, value)	Fills the entire array with a specific value.
________________________________________
4. Comprehensive Java Code Example
Here is a single program demonstrating all the major manipulations and Arrays methods.
Java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class ArrayMastery {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // 1. Initialization
        int[] myNumbers = {5, 2, 9, 1, 6};

        // 2. Accessing and Modifying
        System.out.println("Original first element: " + myNumbers[0]);
        myNumbers[0] = 10; 
        
        // 3. Printing an array (The easy way)
        System.out.println("Current Array: " + Arrays.toString(myNumbers));

        // 4. Sorting
        Arrays.sort(myNumbers);
        System.out.println("Sorted Array: " + Arrays.toString(myNumbers));

        // 5. Binary Search (Must be sorted first!)
        int index = Arrays.binarySearch(myNumbers, 6);
        System.out.println("Index of element 6: " + index);

        // 6. Copying / Resizing
        int[] largerArray = Arrays.copyOf(myNumbers, 10);
        System.out.println("New expanded array: " + Arrays.toString(largerArray));

        // 7. Filling
        int[] blankArray = new int[5];
        Arrays.fill(blankArray, 7);
        System.out.println("Filled Array: " + Arrays.toString(blankArray));

        // 8. Manual Traversal (Looping)
        System.out.print("Manual print: ");
        for (int num : myNumbers) {
            System.out.print(num + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();

        // 9. Comparison
        int[] checkArray = {1, 2, 5, 6, 9}; // Matches myNumbers after sort
        boolean isEqual = Arrays.equals(myNumbers, checkArray);
        System.out.println("Are the arrays equal? " + isEqual);
    }
}
