StringBuilder vs. StringBuffer
Both classes do exactly the same thing, with one major difference: Safety vs. Speed.
●	StringBuilder (The Fast One): Not "Thread-Safe." It's designed for use by a single thread (which is 99% of most apps). Because it doesn't worry about multiple threads, it is significantly faster.
●	StringBuffer (The Safe One): "Thread-Safe" and "Synchronized." It ensures that if two parts of your program try to change the string at the same time, they won't corrupt the data. This extra caution makes it slower.
________________________________________
2. Understanding Capacity
Unlike a standard String, these builders have an internal Capacity.
●	Length: The number of characters actually inside.
●	Capacity: The amount of total storage space currently allocated.
●	How it grows: When you exceed the capacity, the builder automatically creates a larger internal array (usually doubling the size plus two) and copies the old data over.
Pro Tip: If you know you're going to build a 1,000-character string, initialize it with new StringBuilder(1000). This prevents the "expensive" resizing process from happening multiple times.
________________________________________
3. The Hash Code: Creation and Maintenance
In Java, hashCode() is a method that returns an integer representing the "identity" of the object’s data.
For Strings
The hash code for a String is calculated based on its contents using a specific mathematical formula:
$$s[0] \cdot 31^{n-1} + s[1] \cdot 31^{n-2} + \dots + s[n-1]$$
●	Because Strings are immutable, Java calculates the hash code once and caches it. It never changes, which makes Strings perfect keys for HashMap.
For StringBuilder/StringBuffer
●	These classes do not override the hashCode() method from the Object class.
●	Their hash code is based on their memory address, not their content.
●	Warning: Even if two StringBuilder objects contain the exact same text, they will have different hash codes.
________________________________________
4. Comprehensive Code Example
This code demonstrates manipulation, capacity checks, and the hash code behavior.
Java
public class BuilderAndHash {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // 1. Initializing with custom capacity
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(10); 
        
        System.out.println("Initial Capacity: " + sb.capacity()); // 10
        
        // 2. Manipulations
        sb.append("Hello");
        sb.insert(5, " Java");      // "Hello Java"
        sb.replace(0, 5, "Hi");     // "Hi Java"
        sb.reverse();               // "avaJ iH"
        sb.delete(0, 5);            // "iH" (Wait, it's reversed!)
        
        System.out.println("Final Content: " + sb);

        // 3. Capacity Growth
        StringBuilder dynamic = new StringBuilder("Small");
        System.out.println("Start Capacity: " + dynamic.capacity()); // Default is length + 16
        dynamic.append(" This is a very long string to force a resize.");
        System.out.println("New Capacity: " + dynamic.capacity());

        // 4. Hash Code Demonstration
        String str1 = "Java";
        String str2 = "Java";
        System.out.println("String Hash (Content-based): " + str1.hashCode());
        System.out.println("Matches str2? " + (str1.hashCode() == str2.hashCode()));

        StringBuilder sb1 = new StringBuilder("Java");
        StringBuilder sb2 = new StringBuilder("Java");
        System.out.println("SB1 Hash (Address-based): " + sb1.hashCode());
        System.out.println("SB2 Hash (Address-based): " + sb2.hashCode());
        // Notice: sb1.hashCode() != sb2.hashCode() even though content is the same!
    }
}

Strings (str1.hashCode() == str2.hashCode())
●	In Java, the String class overrides hashCode() to compute a value based on the sequence of characters.
●	Formula:
hashCode=s[0]\cdot 31^{n-1}+s[1]\cdot 31^{n-2}+\dots +s[n-1]
●	where s[i] is the Unicode value of the character.
●	So, two Strings with the same characters will always have the same hash code, even if they are different objects in memory.
StringBuilder (sb1.hashCode() and sb2.hashCode())
●	Unlike String, the StringBuilder class does not override hashCode().
●	It inherits the default implementation from Object, which is typically derived from the object’s memory address.
●	That means two different StringBuilder objects with the same content will almost always have different hash codes, because they are distinct objects in memory.
Thread Safe vs. Not Thread Safe
Not Thread Safe (StringBuilder)
If a class is not thread safe, it means it does not have any internal protection.
●	The Risk: If Thread A is adding "Hello" and Thread B is adding "World" at the same time, the internal character array might skip a letter or crash (throw an exception).
●	The Benefit: It is extremely fast because it doesn't waste time checking if someone else is using it.
Thread Safe (StringBuffer)
If a class is thread safe, it guarantees that the internal data will remain consistent even if multiple threads attack it at once.
●	The Mechanism: It uses Locks. If Thread A is using the object, Thread B must wait in line until Thread A is finished.
+1
●	The Downside: It is slower because of the overhead of managing those "waits" and "locks."
________________________________________
2. Synchronized vs. Not Synchronized
These terms describe how thread safety is actually implemented in the code.
Synchronized
In Java, the synchronized keyword is a "lock." When a method is synchronized:
1.	A thread "grabs the key" to the object.
2.	It performs its work (like append).
3.	It "releases the key."
4.	StringBuffer has almost all its methods marked as synchronized.
Not Synchronized
A method that is not synchronized has no "lock."
1.	Any thread can enter the method at any time.
2.	StringBuilder methods are not synchronized.
________________________________________
3. StringBuilder vs. StringBuffer: The Showdown
Feature	StringBuilder	StringBuffer
Thread Safety	No (Not Thread Safe)	Yes (Thread Safe)
Synchronization	No (Not Synchronized)	Yes (Synchronized)
Speed	Fast (High performance)	Slower (Locking overhead)
When to use?	99% of the time (Single-thread)	Rare (Multi-threaded shared logic)
Introduced	Java 1.5	Java 1.0 (Old school)
